<style>
    {% capture stylesheet %}
    :root {
      --space-base: 1rem;

      {% comment %}
        Spacing tokens are inherently responsive via clamp().
        ALL tiers — built-ins (xs/sm/md/lg/xl/2xl/3xl) AND per-site
        synth tiers — live in `theme.space_scale`. Built-in defaults
        ship via settings_schema.json presets; transpiler synthesizes
        additional tiers when source has responsive spacing pairs
        (e.g. `px-6 xl:px-16` → `synth-1_5-4_0rem`).
        Each entry is either:
          - { value: '<length>' }  → flat token
          - { min, max, vw }       → clamp(min, vw, max) responsive token
      {% endcomment %}
      {% for s in space_scale %}
        {% unless s[1].settings.structural %}
          {% if s[1].settings.value != blank %}
      --space-{{ s[0] }}: {{ s[1].settings.value }};
          {% elsif s[1].settings.min != blank and s[1].settings.max != blank %}
      --space-{{ s[0] }}: clamp({{ s[1].settings.min }}, {{ s[1].settings.vw | default: '5vw' }}, {{ s[1].settings.max }});
          {% endif %}
        {% endunless %}
      {% endfor %}
    }

    {% comment %}
      Single source of truth for spacing class rules — emitted from
      `theme.space_scale`. Structural tiers (`none`, `custom`) have
      specialized CSS in theme.css and skip this loop.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% for s in space_scale %}
      {% unless s[1].settings.structural %}
      .padding-py-{{ s[0] }} { padding-top: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); padding-bottom: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      .padding-px-{{ s[0] }} { padding-left: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); padding-right: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      .margin-my-{{ s[0] }} { margin-top: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); margin-bottom: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      .margin-mx-{{ s[0] }} { margin-left: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); margin-right: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      .gap-{{ s[0] }} { gap: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      .direction-row.gap-{{ s[0] }}, .direction-responsive.gap-{{ s[0] }} { --children-gap: var(--space-{{ s[0] }}); }
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}

    :root {

      --type-scale: {{ typography.type_scale | divided_by: 100.0 }};
      --radius-global: {{ layout.corner_radius }}px;

      {% for scheme in font_schemes %} --font-{{ scheme[0] }}: "{{ scheme[1].settings.name }}", sans-serif; {% endfor %}

      {% comment %}
        --- Brand palette tokens ---
        Each entry in the palette group emits a single CSS custom property at
        :root. Slot values inside surfaces reference these via @palette-id
        which the surface block below resolves to var(--palette-X).
      {% endcomment %}
      {% for token in palette %} --palette-{{ token[0] }}: {{ token[1].settings.value }}; {% endfor %}

      {% comment %}
        --- Brand gradient tokens ---
        Site-defined gradients (linear/radial/conic). Block-level
        `*_role: gradient` references these via `var(--gradient-id)`.
        Composite by nature so they don't fold into a palette token —
        keeping them centralized here means a brand-redesign edit
        propagates to every surface that paints with the gradient.
      {% endcomment %}
      {% for token in gradients %} --gradient-{{ token[0] }}: {{ token[1].settings.value }}; {% endfor %}
    }

    {% comment %}
      --- Surfaces ---
      Each slot emits one CSS custom property. Slot values may be:
        @palette-id     → resolves to var(--palette-id)
        #aabbcc         → solid hex
        rgba(...)       → solid rgba
        linear-gradient → gradient image (consumed via `background:` shorthand)
        ""              → unset (defaults to transparent)
    {% endcomment %}

    {% for surface in surfaces %}
      {%- assign s = surface[1].settings -%}
      .surface-{{ surface[0] }} {
         {% assign slots = 'background|background_alt|surface|surface_alt|accent_bg|button_bg|control_bg|text|text_secondary|text_subtle|text_emphasis|text_on_accent|text_on_button|text_on_control|border|border_emphasis|shadow' | split: '|' %}
        {%- for slot_id in slots -%}
          {%- assign slot_val = s[slot_id] | default: '' -%}
          {%- assign css_var = '--' | append: slot_id | replace: '_', '-' -%}
          {% assign first_slot_char = slot_val | slice: 0, 1 %}
          {%- if slot_val == blank -%}
            {{ css_var }}: transparent;
          {%- elsif first_slot_char == '@' -%}
            {%- assign ref = slot_val | remove_first: '@' -%}
            {{ css_var }}: var(--palette-{{ ref }});
          {%- else -%}
            {{ css_var }}: {{ slot_val }};
          {%- endif -%}
        {%- endfor -%}
      }
    {% endfor %}

    {% comment %}
      Width — site-defined container scale + fixed structural variants.
      Container-tier classes only set `--limit-width`; the `.limit-width`
      utility class (from theme.css) is responsible for applying the
      var as `max-width` and centering. This matches the legacy contract
      and avoids forcing `width: 100%` / `margin-inline: auto` on blocks
      that should flow naturally (which caused alignment regressions).
    {% endcomment %}
    {% comment %}
      Container scale loop: skip `structural: true` entries because
      they have specialized CSS rules below (flex: 0 0 X% on
      half/third/quarter, fit-content sizing on fit/fill) that the
      loop's `--limit-width: <value>` emit can't replicate. The
      structural entries still appear in `theme.container_scale` so
      the editor's width picker lists them.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% comment %}
      Container tiers split into two groups:
      - `synth-*` (synthesized from source `w-N` Tailwind) are FIXED
        widths — icon containers etc. need to hold their size even
        when a flex parent has `align-items: center` (which would
        otherwise shrink them to content). Emit explicit `width:`.
      - All other named tiers (canvas, extra-wide, c-* from inline
        `max-width:`, named anchors) are MAX-width caps. Element
        fills parent up to the cap. Emit only `--limit-width:`,
        block-limit-width handles `width: 100%; max-width: var(...)`.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% for c in container_scale %}
      {% unless c[1].settings.structural %}
        {% if c[0] contains 'synth-' %}
          {%- comment -%}
            Synth tiers represent literal pixel widths from source `w-N`
            (icon backgrounds, fixed-size containers etc.). They MUST
            keep their declared width — `flex-shrink: 0` prevents a
            sibling with flex-grow from compressing the icon below 48px
            and rendering it as an oval. Different from `width-fit`
            (where shrinking-to-fit IS desired in tight viewports).
          {%- endcomment -%}
          .width-{{ c[0] }} { --limit-width: {{ c[1].settings.max_width | default: '100%' }}; width: {{ c[1].settings.max_width | default: '100%' }}; max-width: 100%; flex-shrink: 0; }
        {% else %}
          .width-{{ c[0] }} { --limit-width: {{ c[1].settings.max_width | default: '100%' }}; }
        {% endif %}
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}

    {% comment %}
      Direction-breakpoint media queries — emitted per container_scale
      tier so block settings can reference any tier name for "switch
      from column to row at this width". This unifies the breakpoint
      vocabulary with the width vocabulary: each container tier
      doubles as a breakpoint reference. group.liquid emits a
      `bp-<tier>` modifier class from `direction_breakpoint`. Skip
      structural tiers (auto/full/fit/half/etc.) and any tier whose
      max_width isn't a pixel/rem length.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% comment %}
      Reverse-order modifier (responsive_order_override: reverse on group):
      below the breakpoint (column mode), flip child order. Above the
      breakpoint, the per-tier `bp-<tier>` rules below set
      `flex-direction: row` which overrides column-reverse — so children
      render in source order at desktop. Mirrors Tailwind's
      `flex-col-reverse <bp>:flex-row`. Placed BEFORE the bp media
      queries so cascade order ensures desktop rules win.
    {% endcomment %}
    .direction-responsive.responsive-order-reverse { flex-direction: column-reverse; }

    {% for c in container_scale %}
      {% unless c[1].settings.structural %}
        {% assign mw = c[1].settings.max_width %}
        {% if mw contains 'rem' or mw contains 'px' %}
        @media (min-width: {{ mw }}) { .direction-responsive.bp-{{ c[0] }} { flex-direction: row; } }
        {% endif %}
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}

    {% comment %}
      Default `direction-responsive` (no `bp-*` modifier) — switches to
      row at md=768 to match mise's prior hardcoded behavior. Lets
      blocks like `_header-actions` that don't emit a bp-* modifier
      still get the column→row switch they expect. Specificity is
      lower than `.direction-responsive.bp-*`, so explicit bp blocks
      still win.
    {% endcomment %}
    @media (min-width: 768px) {
      .direction-responsive:not([class*="bp-"]) { flex-direction: row; }
    }

    .width-fit  { --limit-width: fit-content; width: fit-content; }
    .width-fill { --limit-width: 100%; width: 100%; }
    .width-half    { --limit-width: 50%;     flex: 0 0 calc(50%     - (var(--children-gap, 0px) * 1) / 2); }
    .width-third   { --limit-width: 33.333%; flex: 0 0 calc(33.333% - (var(--children-gap, 0px) * 2) / 3); }
    .width-quarter { --limit-width: 25%;     flex: 0 0 calc(25%     - (var(--children-gap, 0px) * 3) / 4); }

    {% comment %}
      Half/third/quarter assume the row holds an equal-width set
      (2/3/4 children). With gap on the parent flex, each child must
      give back its share of the gap so the row sums to 100%:
      `(N-1) * gap` total → each loses `(N-1)/N * gap`.

      We can't read the gap directly via inheritance: every block
      sets its own `--space-gap` (gap-custom) or uses one of the
      named tokens (`--space-xs/sm/md/lg/xl`), so a child shadows
      whatever the parent declared. Instead the parent ROW re-
      exposes its actual gap as `--children-gap` via compound
      selectors — these match only when an element is *both*
      direction-row/responsive AND has a specific gap-* class.
      A child card inside (direction-column) won't match, so
      `--children-gap` propagates cleanly via inheritance.
    {% endcomment %}
    .direction-row, .direction-responsive { --children-gap: 0px; }
    .direction-row.gap-custom, .direction-responsive.gap-custom { --children-gap: var(--space-gap); }
    {% comment %}
      Per-tier `--children-gap` mappings are emitted alongside the
      `.gap-<tier>` rules above (single loop, single source of truth).
    {% endcomment %}


    @media (max-width: 767px) {
      {% comment %}
        Mobile collapse: half/third/quarter become full-width.
        `flex-basis` semantics depend on parent direction —
        `0 0 100%` in flex-row means "full width per child" (correct,
        each card on its own row), but in flex-col it means "full
        HEIGHT per child" (wrong — each child consumes full parent
        height, ballooning the page). Scope the flex rule to row/
        responsive parents; for column parents set `width: 100%`.
      {% endcomment %}
      {% comment %}
        At mobile, direction-responsive parents resolve to column
        (axis-swap CSS in theme.css), so children share the column
        semantics: flex-basis is HEIGHT, not width. Group responsive
        with column for the mobile-collapse rule.
      {% endcomment %}
      .direction-row > .width-half,
      .direction-row > .width-third,
      .direction-row > .width-quarter
        { --limit-width: 100%; flex: 0 0 100%; }
      .direction-column > .width-half,
      .direction-column > .width-third,
      .direction-column > .width-quarter,
      .direction-responsive > .width-half,
      .direction-responsive > .width-third,
      .direction-responsive > .width-quarter
        { --limit-width: 100%; width: 100%; max-width: 100%; flex-basis: auto; }
      .direction-responsive > .width-fit { --limit-width: 100%; }
    }

    {% comment %}
      Height scale loop: same structural-skip rule the width loop
      uses. The loop emits `height: <value>` for every non-structural
      tier in `height_scale` (anchored or synthesized). Structural
      entries (`auto` / `full`) get specialized rules immediately
      below — `.height-full` carries `flex: 1 1 0%` so the block
      participates in flex stretch correctly, which the loop's
      value-only emit can't replicate. Sections that previously
      rendered as `is-sm`/`is-md`/`is-lg`/`is-xl` now use the same
      tier vocabulary so block + section heights share one system.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% comment %}
      Each height_scale tier carries both a value AND a `floor` flag:
        - `floor: true`  → emits `min-height: VALUE; height: auto`
                           (block grows past tier if content taller)
        - `floor: false` → emits `height: VALUE` (fixed render height)
      `--tier-height` always carries the value so layout-section overrides
      (hero, section) can read it as `min-height` for their own always-floor
      behavior, regardless of the tier's flag.

      This puts the fixed-vs-floor decision on the SCALE itself — any
      block consuming the tier inherits the right semantic. No block-level
      override needed. Maps cleanly to source: `h-N` picks a fixed tier
      (default), `min-h-N` picks a floor tier (transpiler mints `synth-min-Xrem`
      / `synth-min-100vh` etc.).
    {% endcomment %}
    {% for h in height_scale %}
      {% unless h[1].settings.structural %}
        {% if h[1].settings.value != blank %}
          {% if h[1].settings.floor_fill %}
        .height-{{ h[0] }} { --tier-height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; min-height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; height: 100%; flex: 1 1 {{ h[1].settings.value }}; }
          {% elsif h[1].settings.floor %}
        .height-{{ h[0] }} { --tier-height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; min-height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; height: auto; }
          {% else %}
        .height-{{ h[0] }} { --tier-height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; height: {{ h[1].settings.value }}; }
          {% endif %}
        {% elsif h[1].settings.min != blank and h[1].settings.max != blank %}
          {% capture clamp_expr %}clamp({{ h[1].settings.min }}, {{ h[1].settings.vw | default: '40vw' }}, {{ h[1].settings.max }}){% endcapture %}
          {% if h[1].settings.floor %}
        .height-{{ h[0] }} { --tier-height: {{ clamp_expr }}; min-height: {{ clamp_expr }}; height: auto; }
          {% else %}
        .height-{{ h[0] }} { --tier-height: {{ clamp_expr }}; height: {{ clamp_expr }}; }
          {% endif %}
        {% endif %}
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}

    .height-auto { height: auto; }
    .height-full { height: 100%; flex: 1 1 0%; min-height: 0; }
    .height-custom { height: var(--block-height, auto); }

    {% comment %}
      Type tiers (.fs-<id>) — flat (`value`) or responsive clamp
      (`min`/`max`/`vw`). Source HTML's `text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl
      lg:text-8xl` pattern can mint a single clamp tier scaling between
      the smallest and largest sizes — preserving responsive typography
      that a flat tier can't express. Built-in tiers (jumbo/display/
      h1..h6/body/small/caption) ship flat at Tailwind-equivalent values.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% for t in text_scale %}
      {% unless t[1].settings.structural %}
        {% if t[1].settings.value != blank %}
        .fs-{{ t[0] }} { font-size: {{ t[1].settings.value }}; }
        {% elsif t[1].settings.min != blank and t[1].settings.max != blank %}
        .fs-{{ t[0] }} { font-size: clamp({{ t[1].settings.min }}, {{ t[1].settings.vw | default: '5vw' }}, {{ t[1].settings.max }}); }
        {% endif %}
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}

    .font-heading { font-family: var(--font-{{ typography.heading_font_scheme }}); }
    .font-body    { font-family: var(--font-{{ typography.body_font_scheme }}); }
    .font-button  { font-family: var(--font-{{ typography.button_font_scheme }}); }
    {% comment %}
      Per-scheme `.font-{key}` utility classes. Mirrors the source's
      Tailwind-config `fontFamily` keys (e.g. `accent: ["Kalam",
      "cursive"]` → `class="font-accent"`). Without this loop, only
      heading/body/button utilities get a CSS rule and any
      brand-extended family class falls through to the inherited
      font (visible as the wrong typeface on accent/script/display
      headings).

      Structural schemes (`heading`, `body`, `button`) are flagged
      `structural: true` in settings_schema.json and SKIPPED here —
      they have dedicated rules above that pull from the typography
      mapping vars (`heading_font_scheme` etc.), not the scheme name
      directly. Emitting again would duplicate and conflict.
    {% endcomment %}
    {% for scheme in font_schemes %}
      {% unless scheme[1].settings.structural %}
      .font-{{ scheme[0] }} { font-family: var(--font-{{ scheme[0] }}); }
      {% endunless %}
    {% endfor %}
  {% endcapture %}
  {{ stylesheet | strip_newlines }}
</style>
